'''Moira pottery works''', founded in 1922, was known for its utilitarian [[stoneware]] crocks for marmalade and inexpensive pitchers and other kitchen wares, sometimes applied with [[transfer-print]]ed advertising reproducing quaint turn-of-the-century woodcuts. The company's "Hillstonia" ware was intended for forcing bulbs and containing plants.

Moira pottery was often marked with an oval stamp on the unglazed undersides of its production. The pottery works was situated approximately 5&nbsp;mi (8&nbsp;km) from [[Burton-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], although the village of [[Moira, Leicestershire|Moira]] is just over the border in [[Leicestershire]].

The plant was closed by the [[National Coal Board]] and its buildings razed in 1972 under [[eminent domain|compulsory purchase]], because the land it stood on was over a coal reserve. After the [[Open-pit mining|open-pit]] coal seam was exhausted the land was reclaimed and is planted as part of the [[National Forest, England|National Forest]].

